Fifteen‭ ‬years ago I became suddenly and unexpectedly disabled by an illness I never knew existed. 

 I was a nurse at the time. I had chosen my profession out of a deeply entrenched need for the safety and security I didn't have as a child. ‭"‬You'll always be able to find work‭; ‬people will always get sick.‭" ‬was the mantra I heard over and over as I reached adolescence and beyond. So--‭ ‬even though my dream was to be a scientist or a journalist-preferably a little of both,‭ ‬I chose nursing. 

Nevertheless,‭ ‬there I was:‭ ‬46‭ ‬years old and single,‭ ‬no money in the bank to speak of and unable to work. To this day I am disabled,‭ ‬and after‭ ‬15‭ ‬years of living on Social Security Disability,‭ ‬I have literally nothing left that I can call‭ "‬mine.‭" ‬I get by,‭ ‬but every day is a struggle and an assault on my security,‭ ‬safety and self-esteem. Nothing in my life is certain anymore,‭ ‬yet,‭ ‬there is one thing that I know to be true. I could not have gotten by for all these years were it not for the help of my family and a few good friends,‭ ‬no matter how strong I was. And believe me,‭ ‬when real disaster strikes,‭ ‬you do not feel very strong at all. 

My point is that there will always be emergencies in life-big and small.  There are no guarantees and no matter how well one prepares,‭ ‬some things are just too big to overcome on your own. 

I agree wholeheartedly that we in the U.S. need to stop putting all of our eggs in big government's‭ "‬basket‭"; ‬Lord knows it is moldy‭ ‬and falling apart,‭ ‬anyway. Yet I would much rather see Americans learning to trust one another again‭–‬learning to help each other and to ask for help,‭ ‬rather‭ ‬than have each of us individually clambering out to the backyard to build fallout shelters. 

The Conservatives in the US talk about the‭ "‬rugged individualism‭" ‬that built this country‭; ‬but in truth,‭ ‬what kept our forefathers going in hard times wasn't rugged individualism,‭ ‬it was compassion,‭ ‬mutual respect and the sharing of resources. The pioneers who crossed the Rockies in wagon trains didn't make it to the coast by going it alone. 


So,‭ ‬by all means,‭ ‬be prepared. I am. I have a disaster kit‭; ‬first‭ ‬aid supplies,‭ ‬water purifying tablets and plastic sheeting and duct tape for the windows in the event of a biological attack. I have several flashlights and all sorts of batteries,‭ ‬lots and lots of candles and waterproof matches and canned goods,‭ ‬too. If‭ ‬you have the land and the resources for a small farm and the ability to can or preserve your own food-do it. It's a great idea,‭ ‬as is a wood stove,‭ ‬as long as you do not live in an apartment. 

But while you are at it,‭ ‬get to know your neighbors.

Sometime in the fifth or sixth century BCE, a prince who would one day be called Buddha was born. Over the course of his life, he renounced the world and became enlightened, and his teachings led to the formation of Buddhism—the most orthodox sect of which is known as Theravada Buddhism. The religion is around twenty five hundred years old; it looks different today than it did when Buddha was alive. This can be seen all over, for instance in the Theravada nation of Sri Lanka, where the annual water-cutting ceremony is observed. Monks and laymen alike participate in this ceremony, and it holds some religious significance, despite Buddha never teaching about any festivity of the sort. These differences run all the way from the superficial traditions to the soteriological core of the religion. The Theravada Buddhist community, both from the monastic perspective and from the lay perspective, has had to change its doctrinal principles over time. This can be attributed to forces both external and internal, both hostile and benign.
	There are a number of qualifying terms this discussion will make frequent use of. There is the concept of internal versus external. Here, an internal force is defined as a force borne of members of the Buddhasasana, regardless of monastic status. An external force is any force from non-Buddhists. A hostile force is any force that damages or intends to damage the Buddhist community—a force borne of a negative perception of Buddhism. A benign force is a force that does not wish to harm or help the Buddhist community—though it may end up doing one or the other as a byproduct. These terms will come up repeatedly throughout this discussion.
	First, it is important to investigate the basics of the religion—the doctrines that lie at the core of Theravada Buddhism. Buddhists seek refuge in the triple gem of the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma is essentially comprised of the Tripitaka—the three baskets—of Buddhist text. The Sutta Pitaka contains all the Suttas, the Vinaya Pitaka contains the disciplinary rules, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka contains the metaphysical components of Buddhism. The metaphysical notions consist of things like Anatta—no soul, Dukkha—inherent suffering in life, and Anicca—impermanence of everything. Only by recognizing these concepts can one end Sansara, the cycle of death and rebirth, which happens continuously. Along with Sansara will end lobha—desire, dosa—hatred, and moha—delusion, when one becomes enlightened. In the Vinaya Pitaka, rules for life are set forth. For laymen, there are five precepts (I shall not kill, I shall not lie, I shall not steal, I shall not misbehave sexually, and I shall not take intoxicating substances). For monks, there are many more disciplinary rules to be followed. The most fundamental doctrinal notion in Buddhism is the notion of the four noble truths. First, Dukkha; the truth that life is suffering. Second, that attachment causes suffering. Third, that suffering can be overcome.

Culture plays a crucial role in any negotiation. It can be defined as much by what it is not as by what it actually is and what it signifies. Culture is neither homogeneous nor a specific entity. It is also not singular or uniform. Statements like “all Russians are stubborn” or “all Japanese are accommodating” are inherently broad and overly simplistic. While understanding the generalizations of a culture is appropriate, it is far more productive for a negotiator to grasp the significance of a culture to the matter at hand and how that culture’s attitude can affect negotiations. When approaching a foreign culture, one experiences it in a manner relatable to one's own culture, and comparisons naturally arise.

Understanding a foreign culture or mindset can involve anything from studying its history to recognizing its prejudices. Rather than judging or trying to change a culture, one must accept it as it is and work within its boundaries, especially in the context of negotiation, and particularly if one comes to the table with a weaker bargaining position. Similarly, respecting traditions and beliefs when a negotiator is on "foreign" territory can only help to overcome cultural barriers and advance the negotiation.

It is important to note that culture does not necessarily confine itself to a national/international dichotomy. Most companies within a certain nation establish their own corporate culture. For example, a corporate culture might emphasize long office hours or a more relaxed schedule. Evidence of corporate culture can be seen in employee dress codes, communication styles (direct vs. indirect communication, delegation of duties), and hiring practices. Some companies encourage philanthropy at any level from employees, while others restrict it to “company-approved” charities or fundraisers. Observing differences in American corporate culture from company to company (and indeed, intra-company diversity exists even from region to region, including urban to suburban environments) demonstrates the diversity of thought that can exist within a particular societal culture. Certain cultures are not nearly as stratified as American culture and may appear more uniform to an outsider, but a similar exterior simply indicates a need to dig deeper.

Values are even more important to understand because they provide the rationale behind a culture. If saving face or communal harmony is valued within a culture, a negotiator will certainly not publicly shame his company or superior to succeed at the negotiation table. Similarly, a negotiator from a culture that places greater importance on hard-driven bargaining will not necessarily be inclined to settle at the earliest opportunity. Taking these generalities into account is crucial before one reaches the negotiating table. However, it is beneficial for a negotiator to learn something personal about his opponent to make the negotiation effective.

"The fool says in his heart, 'There is no God.'" This quote first appears in Psalm 14 of the Christian Bible and is at the beginning of St. Anselm's argument about God's existence. This belief seems to be shared by another author we will discuss, Thomas Aquinas. Since both arguments defend the same concept, and our task is to determine which is superior, we must, for the sake of brevity, assume they are both correct in their belief in the existence of God, specifically the God of the Bible. Assuming a God-type figure different from the one in which our two authors believe would not allow us to adequately compare their arguments, as they essentially defend a specific concept of God. That said, I would suggest that while both present valid points, neither truly provides a comprehensive basis for belief in God. To illustrate this, we will first examine St. Anselm's basic argument. Anselm's passage reflects a path of gaining understanding through faith by looking within oneself for proof of God. He explains that since God exists in our understanding, we cannot effectively conceive of his nonexistence. While this concept, when explained in his terms, is somewhat tedious and at times unclear, the main idea is that the proof of God lies within one's own mind. St. Anselm suggests that we don't need to go beyond the confines of our soul to find the truth about God, but that the existence of this being is considered true simply by examining what we inherently know to be true within our own minds. Foreign evidence is presumably unnecessary. This concept of accepting something without an irrefutable body of empirical evidence is often referred to in Christian texts as faith. This idea is quite different from that of St. Thomas Aquinas. Aquinas proposes that the existence of God can be entirely proven through reason and empirical evidence, without any need for faith. Such an idea would be advantageous in evangelism, an important element of Christianity, as it would allow for the recruitment of new converts without relying on their willingness to accept something unproven. Instead, they could be convinced by logic alone. St. Thomas elaborates on five different logical arguments supporting the existence of God: change, causation, contingency, degrees of excellence, and harmony. In each, he essentially demonstrates that the proof of God lies in the logical necessity for God. If you're told that you are missing a puzzle piece and assemble the rest of the puzzle, logic dictates that you can know the features and existence of the missing piece without having to see it."

Many authors employ different methods to convey a certain feeling or attitude towards important subjects to their readers. Some of these techniques are more effective than others. F. Scott Fitzgerald uses a variety of these techniques in his novel The Great Gatsby. Sometimes, Fitzgerald pairs an adjective with a noun that usually don't fit together to create a certain aura around a subject for the readers. At other times, he assigns meaning to a symbol and then uses it for the same purpose. Fitzgerald employs this latter technique with many colors, including gold, green, white/gray, and red/pink. In his novel The Great Gatsby, F. Scott Fitzgerald builds meanings for colors, particularly white/gray and red/pink, and later uses these meanings to evoke a certain feeling around an important object for readers.

The meaning Fitzgerald develops and uses for white/gray is uniformity, with white being somewhat nicer and higher class, and gray being older and more faded. Fitzgerald establishes this meaning at the beginning of the novel through the constant use of both colors. Daisy and Jordan are consistently "in white"—in fact, everyone is always wearing white: Nick wears "white flannels" to Gatsby's party, Tom wears a "white shirt" when he meets Myrtle, and Catherine is "powdered milky white." The only time people aren't wearing white is when Nick gets his impressions of Gatsby's party: "the halls... are gaudy with primary colors." Fitzgerald further defines these two colors by coloring many common, unimportant subjects with them: as Nick goes to work, he travels "down the white chasms of lower New York," the names of people at Gatsby's parties are now "gray names" on Nick's timetable, Catherine's apartment is "one slice in a long white cake of apartment-houses"—uniformity. He also describes plain or common people or places as white or gray: Jordan and Daisy had a "white girlhood" together, there are "gray cars" and "gray land" in the valley of ashes, the "Italian child" on the railroad is "gray," and the dog-seller is "a gray old man."

After Fitzgerald has imbued white/gray with enough meaning, he uses them to signify unimportance or uniformity in certain subjects. This use of colors to show something to readers first starts with Daisy. After a long period without significant use of either color, Fitzgerald describes Daisy as "dressed in white" in "a little white roadster"; readers begin to see Daisy less as a character, more like a uniform addition, something that Gatsby desires and longs for. Fitzgerald employs more of this technique around Daisy to give the impression of her being a more uniform addition, for instance, there is a "gray haze of Daisy's fur collar," and she is again in a "white" dress before Tom and Gatsby's encounter.

San Diego County is highly productive agriculturally, thanks to its mild, sunny climate. Common crops include tomatoes, citrus fruits, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, tree fruits like peaches and lemons, berries, honey, and peppers. There is a significant market for food from organic, community-supported agriculture in the San Diego area, with many local organizations having long waiting lists. Organic eggs and milk are also popular. Many organic farms offer tours of their agricultural operations as well as access for hiking, birdwatching, and other recreational activities. This type of operation allows the landowner to benefit from government programs while improving habitats, permitting recreational use, and creating opportunities for farm tours and other income-generating or educational activities.

In addition to filling a potentially lucrative niche market, the benefits of organic farming often include greater biodiversity in local plants and wildlife due to the absence of chemicals in the soil and water. However, organic farming entails higher costs than conventional farming in some respects. It requires more intensive labor and management to remove pests and weeds and fertilize the soil without chemicals, and losses are often greater than with conventional methods. A small organic farm also lacks the efficiency of large-scale operations. Practices not associated with organic farming but beneficial to wildlife can also lead to higher labor costs, such as planting cover crops, strategic grazing rotation, invasive species removal, and active management of plant growth to create specific conditions like edge habitats or open patches. Thus, there are many reasons why the landowner in this example might seek financial assistance or expertise to maximize both profits and habitat quality.

The land chosen for this scenario is a parcel next to the town of Potrero in unincorporated San Diego County, California. It comprises 160 acres of chaparral, nonnative Mediterranean grassland, and oak woodland adjacent to the Cleveland National Forest. It lies in the East County Southern Foothills ecoregion of the San Diego Multiple Species Conservation Plan. The plan is still under review but currently considers over a hundred plant and animal species. Many of these are endangered, such as the Stephens' kangaroo rat, the mountain yellow-legged frog, several butterfly species, and the California gnatcatcher; others are declining and may soon be listed, like burrowing owls.

This area was inhabited by Native Americans for countless centuries and was later settled by cattle ranchers and cordwood sellers in the late 1800s. This piece of land was part of an original homestead patent and was likely used for grazing and/or wood production over many intervening decades.

I selected a piece of property from a real estate website and researched available government programs to explore what options a small farmer might realistically have for reducing costs and maintaining wildlife-friendly operations. As a model of what someone farming this land might aim to achieve, I identified an organic farm in the same area.

There is a bond between brothers; an unbreakable, irrevocable connection. Within this bond lie many emotions: love, pride, jealousy, and cruelty, just to name a few. Brothers understand each other far more than anyone else with such a bond, and they can only see themselves when they look at their brother. It is in the most critical situations that the true nature of this bond is revealed, whether good or evil. When these emotions become clear, they come with a high cost. Part of understanding the emotions born from this fraternal link is dealing with the consequences they bring. When one can look a brother in the eye and see their own reflection, they see themselves not as others see them, but as they truly are. In their actions and the resulting consequences is where their true character lies. In “The Scarlet Ibis,” two brothers explore this theme and all the raging emotions that accompany it. Throughout a lush, vividly described landscape, these two boys embark on a futile journey. Bitter disappointment clashes with intense pride in the climactic scene, and only one brother escapes with his life. The theme is expressed through the direct characterization of the protagonist, Doodle, and their interactions with each other, as well as through the narrator’s perspective, which conveys the complex feelings experienced by the protagonist and his view of the world around him, both of which strongly influence his actions.  
The protagonist’s actions can all be summed up by one key emotion: pride. From the moment he and his little brother, Doodle, first set out together, to their final, fateful excursion, the protagonist feels resentment toward Doodle. He wanted a brother to whom he could teach all his worldly skills, like “...holding my breath, running, jumping, or climbing the vines in Old Woman Swamp...” He wanted a brother who could fill the role of “...someone to race to Horsehead Landing... and someone to perch with in the top fork of the great pine behind the barn...” Obviously, these things are impossible, given Doodle’s condition. Doodle was born with an extremely weak heart, making it unlikely that he would even survive. Even then, it was almost impossible that he would ever participate in vigorous physical activity. What a blow to the young protagonist, whose head was filled with wild fantasies, to see all those dreams crushed in an instant. In fact, he is even shown to harbor some anger toward the small child, as he recalls contemplating killing him by suffocating him with a pillow. What kind of child would have the presence of mind to consider infanticide? However, his heart melts when the small child smiles at him. Such a simple act gave the protagonist such hope! This shows that his conviction was probably not very strong. In the back of his mind, he had an instinctive love for his brother.

The human brain is a complex and creative system for processing information. As technology evolved from primitive to modern, the metaphors used to describe the brain also evolved. Initially, it was likened to a wax tablet, then to a papyrus sheet, then a book, and most recently, to a computer. As you study the brain, remember that these metaphors have limitations and can lead to incorrect conclusions.

Information processing begins with input from the sensory organs, which convert physical stimuli like touch, heat, sound waves, or photons of light into electrochemical signals. The brain’s algorithms repeatedly transform sensory information in both bottom-up and top-down processing. For example, when looking at an image of a black box on a white background, bottom-up processing assembles basic information like color, orientation, and the object’s borders—where the color changes significantly over a short distance—to determine that you are seeing a box. Top-down processing uses decisions made during some steps of bottom-up processing to speed up the recognition of the box. In this example, top-down processing might help identify the object as a black box rather than a box-shaped hole in the white background.

Once information is processed to a certain extent, an attention filter decides how important the signal is and to which cognitive processes it should be made available. For instance, although your brain processes every blade of grass when you look at your shoes, a healthy attention filter prevents you from noticing them individually. In contrast, you might pick out your name, even in a noisy room. There are many stages of processing, and the results are repeatedly modulated by attention.

For the brain to process information, it must first be stored. There are different types of memory, including sensory, working, and long-term memory. First, information is encoded. There are types of encoding specific to each type of sensory stimulus. For example, verbal input can be encoded structurally, referring to the appearance of the printed word, phonemically, referring to how the word sounds, or semantically, referring to the meaning of the word. Once stored, the information must be maintained. Some animal studies suggest that working memory, which stores information for about 20 seconds, is maintained by an electrical signal looping through a specific series of neurons for a short time. Long-term memory is hypothesized to be maintained in the structure of certain types of proteins.

There are numerous models of how knowledge is organized in the brain, some based on how human subjects retrieve memories, others based on computer science, and others on neurophysiology. The semantic network model states that there are nodes representing concepts, and these nodes are linked based on their relatedness. For instance, in a semantic network, "chair" might be linked to "table," which can be linked to "wooden," and so on.

In 2007, the United States of America was engulfed in a severe financial crisis. Unemployment rose, the housing market collapsed, and many of America's largest and most vital companies were left in ruins. This recession persists today, prompting the question: how did this crisis arise, and how can we prevent it? In essence, the financial crisis was triggered by selfish and naive political decisions that pressured banks and firms into issuing subprime loans into an already immature and inadequate financial system. Meanwhile, Fannie Mae (FNMA) and Freddie Mac (FHLMC) were urged to underwrite and repackage these mortgages into CDOs and CDSs. When borrowers defaulted on these loans, the banks lacked capital reserves and transferred this turmoil onto the repackaged mortgages they had sold, impacting the entire economy.

The financial crisis traces its roots back to 1999 during the Clinton era, as the President sought a second term in office. He aimed to extend his presidency by boosting his popularity. To achieve this, the Clinton administration relaxed lending restrictions, setting the stage for the subprime crisis seven years later. Steven Holmes of the New York Times reported in 1999: "Fannie Mae, the nation's largest underwriter of home mortgages, has been under increasing pressure from the Clinton Administration to expand mortgage loans among low and moderate-income individuals and felt pressure from shareholders to maintain its phenomenal growth in profits." Holmes accurately foresaw the consequences of these actions: "But the government-subsidized corporation may face trouble in an economic downturn, leading to a government bailout similar to that of the savings and loan industry in the 1980s." As detailed in the introduction and as Holmes predicted, ill-advised lending would inevitably lead to the economic meltdown.

Several factors combined to send the economy into a nosedive, one of which was the new and complex structure of mortgages. Adjustable-rate mortgages, mortgage-backed securities, and collateralized debt obligations (CDOs) were extensively used in the years leading up to the crisis, intertwining more sectors of the economy with the housing market. This led to U.S. households and financial markets, in general, becoming over-leveraged in the housing market, leaving them highly vulnerable to even small price changes.

Indeed, the housing bubble burst, and the financial institutions that had purchased these mortgage-backed securities suffered. The top five U.S. investment banks collectively reported $4.1 trillion in mortgage debts in 2007, accounting for about 30% of the USA’s GDP. Ultimately, Bear Sterns and Merrill Lynch were sold at exceptionally low prices, Lehman Brothers was dismantled, and Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley were forced to become commercial banks subject to intense regulation. Fannie and Freddie were $5 trillion in mortgage debt and were placed under government control in September 2008.

Ah, exposition. That part of your story where you spread your writer's wings and soar, captivating everyone with your magnetic, even magical prose. Or the part where your readers doze off and/or hit the "Back" button while muttering your name in frustration. Dr. Merlin is known to shout at her monitor when she finds herself overwhelmed by excessive details, and not even in an entertaining way.

Exposition is not your ally.

My gentle readers are already familiar with the basic writing principle, "Show, don't tell," yet Dr. Merlin still stumbles into lengthy text passages where nothing happens, or worse, too much happens. Exposition is the little devil on your shoulder suggesting that you clear the history to get to the good parts (not to be confused with the devil on the other shoulder encouraging the author to disclose every tiny detail of each character's childhood).

Exposition involves telling the audience what happened, usually in straightforward prose. In film, exposition occurs when one character delivers a dump of information to another, like in "The Rime of the Ancient Mariner." In fiction, it's the author doing the telling.

An example is in order. As you read a story, you learn that the heroine met her beloved at a particular place and time, they married in grand fashion, and her husband was murdered in front of her eyes. You wouldn't expect this entire sequence to span two pages, during which both characters only get two lines of dialogue each. You would expect the author to spend some time on the husband's character, demonstrating through his speech and behavior how deeply he loves his wife, and similarly, you would anticipate the heroine to reveal in various ways how much his presence transformed and enriched her life (especially if the story later directly states this). A proper introduction to the husband's character would allow you to become emotionally invested in his fate and provide insight into the heroine's character: what she saw in him, the depth of their bond, hints about her thoughts, beliefs, and dreams as reflected through the prism of his eyes, and so on. You would mourn his death with her, thereby becoming more connected to the heroine herself.

In short, you would expect depth on the simple storyline: "They met, they married, he died."

As a writer, you need to provide that depth. (*looks at metaphor, sighs, and proceeds*) Sometimes it's tempting to rush through certain aspects. Perhaps you're introducing a new character and you know he was once in the Air Force, is now the night manager of a gas station, was married twice, has no children, enjoys fishing on weekends, secretly dreams of owning the gas station someday, and had Eggs Benedict for breakfast.

I watched two news broadcasts from Columbus, Ohio. The first one, which was "live," was NBC 4 this morning (August 13, 2011). The lead story was about a man in Ashley, Ohio, who had stabbed his wife; her name was not mentioned, but his name was Shad Hostettler. They showed his mugshot, and he looked like pure evil. They devoted only about two minutes to this developing story. The only details they provided were that he had stabbed her multiple times and had been arrested. I think the time they spent on this story was appropriate.

The second story was about an early morning shooting involving Travis Buyers, 18. He was shot in the Sharon Woods area and was critically injured; there were no arrests or suspects at the time. The SWAT Team was investigating the crime. This story seemed short, and I believe that might have been because he was a "black" man or it was a black neighborhood. I have noticed (for years) that minorities are often overlooked when they are victims of a crime. If, for example, a "white" child or adult is kidnapped or missing or a victim of a crime, the media goes into a frenzy, but if it’s a minority, it’s lucky if it’s even mentioned.

The next story was about a gunshot hole found in the Med-Flight helicopter. Details were given about where they thought the incident occurred. It was determined that a .22 caliber bullet from a rifle had hit the helicopter. Crime-Stoppers are offering a five-thousand dollar reward for tips leading to the arrest of the shooter.

The following story concerned the rain and thunderstorms predicted for Saturday afternoon. They said temperatures would remain in the mid to low eighties for the weekend. The segment was a bit short, but they wanted to use it as a "teaser" to keep viewers tuned in.

They also ran a story about a robbery at a Clime Road UDF in Columbus. They said it was a dark-skinned black man who robbed the store, wearing a hoodie sweatshirt. They described him as about six feet tall and weighing around one hundred and fifty pounds. I thought they spent an unusual amount of time emphasizing that he was black and how dark-skinned he was.

Another story was about Rene Rodriguez, a convicted Texas drug kingpin. He had been convicted of conspiring to distribute large amounts of marijuana to Ohio from Texas. One curious thing I noted was that instead of saying he was sentenced to twenty-five years in prison, they said "300" months. I am not sure what the angle was, whether they thought it sounded harsher or what. They also mentioned he was Hispanic; I don’t believe that was really relevant to the story.

An ETF, or exchange-traded fund, is a security designed to track an index, a commodity, or a basket of assets like an index fund, but it is more flexible and trades like a stock on an exchange. An ETF provides the diversification of an index fund and the benefits of owning individual stocks, such as the ability to short sell, buy on margin, and purchase as few as one share per transaction. Although these benefits are highly attractive, ETFs have significantly lower expense ratios than the average mutual fund. Unfortunately, there are some downsides, such as the need to pay a commission on any trade involving ETFs, just as you would with a stock order. Another benefit of ETFs is the wide variety of funds available. Even though these benefits are clearly stated, it's always a good practice for the savvy financial investor to evaluate whether the stated benefits, such as diversification, indeed exist and to what extent. For this purpose, we will examine the ETF IHF and compare it to the top 10 holdings that make up the ETF to determine if the benefits of owning a single ETF come close to those of owning a diversified portfolio of the ten stocks and also to see if there are better configurations of the same stocks that would provide a more optimal Sharpe ratio or return.

To evaluate the ETF, including every holding would be quite unwieldy, so we have decided to include only the top ten holdings, which account for 63.58% of all the assets in the ETF. Below are the top 10 holdings and their percentage of total assets.

To estimate how well these ten stocks represent the ETF IHF as a whole, we can use the current % of assets, normalized to 100%, to calculate each stock's contribution to a portfolio's Beta and Return if the portfolio consisted entirely of these 10 stocks in the proportion established by the ETF's holdings. The calculations of Beta and return are included in the chart below.

From the chart above, it's evident that the return of a portfolio containing only the top 10 holdings is 6.11% higher than that of the ETF, a 16% increase in returns. It's also evident that the Beta of the top ten holdings is 0.12 lower than the ETF as a whole. From the results completed so far, it seems that a portfolio consisting of just the top 10 holdings could provide a higher return with a lower beta. However, there is a possibility that the means of these two portfolios may not be statistically different from each other.

To assess whether these portfolios are statistically different, the standard deviation of each of the top 10 stocks is determined and normalized to 100% to compare their cumulative standard deviation with that of the ETF IHF.

Referring back to Figure 17, there was a steep decline in commuter log submissions in the third month of the project. This was somewhat disheartening, and it's difficult to pinpoint the cause. With winter setting in at a New England campus, there's a noticeable drop in people commuting by bike or on foot, which may partly explain the decline. December also marks the end of the fall semester when everyone is busy finishing schoolwork, processing grades, and so on. Completing the commuter log might have simply fallen off the radar for many people. Additionally, December brings the start of the busy holiday season and the resulting month-long break for students and faculty, during which many don't need to come to campus at all. Classes resume for the spring semester in late January, which could also be a clue to the low number of logs for that month. However, this doesn't fully explain the low submissions for February. One might speculate that any project of this type experiences an initial burst of energy and enthusiasm that naturally wanes. To counter this trend, we launched the Carpool Challenge Week, a special blitz campaign in March to revive the initiative, which did result in increased log submissions for that month. Thus, one of the challenges we faced was maintaining project momentum in light of both a natural decrease in engagement and specifically the issue of holiday and semester breaks in higher education. Another challenge for this project (or any alternative commuting project) is the simple fact that people enjoy the freedom, independence, and flexibility of driving their cars. This is deeply embedded in our culture. Therefore, it is essential to provide incentives for engaging in alternative commuting modes. We offered many prizes in the form of gift certificates to local restaurants, coffee shops, massage therapists, the local independent bookstore, and even some larger national chain stores. However, it would have been interesting to see how some even larger prizes might have affected participation—such as giving away a nice bicycle, hybrid car, or electric car. This could also have helped to address the dip in engagement the project experienced. The nature of the prizes didn't really change during the project. If the prizes had increased in value over the course of the project, that might have helped. The gift cards seemed more than adequate at the project's start, but if we had announced in December the addition of a couple of bicycles, and then in January the addition of a hybrid or electric car, one can only imagine that participation and engagement would have increased rather than decreased.

I decided to watch all fifteen trick films produced between 1895 and 1901 in the Library of Congress's collection of early Edison films. These films typically use creative editing to create illusions. My film analysis focused on describing the poetics of most trick films and examining the unique evolutionary features found in a few of the later films. Primarily, the trick films at the turn of the century are bound to a set, composed in front of a frontal proscenium, show no camera movement, use long and medium shots, and adhere to the strict method of one shot equaling one film. However, some films from the early twentieth century dare to break these guidelines by introducing elements like multiple shots.

One of the most striking features shared by the trick films is their filming in an interior set within the frame of a frontal proscenium. The camera does not move from its proscenium position to follow figures or objects. This composition was very common in early films and has roots in theater and, for trick films, vaudeville and magic acts. One limitation of using the stage is that figures in trick films generally move only side-to-side and do not walk towards or away from the camera. Take, for example, the action in the film Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel (1900). The actors enter from the right side and move back and forth along the horizontal axis. Even when they go out of frame, the camera does not follow them.

The frontal proscenium style of composition also means that the shots tend to be long shots and, more rarely, medium shots. Close-ups are never used in any of the trick films from the Edison catalog. This is borrowed from the theater and vaudeville tradition, where the audience would see the entire performance at any given time, framed by the edges of the stage. As in most early films, actors do not move from the middle ground towards the camera, so close-ups never occur.

Generally, most early trick films follow the pattern that one conceptual shot equals a film. This limits the length of most trick films to about a minute or less, depending on the frames per second used. It also limits the dramatic or narrative use of the trick films; most focus on short vaudeville-style tricks, such as magic, disappearing, and switching acts with little story. However, note that in a trick film, one conceptual shot in the viewer's eyes does not actually equal one physical shot. A single "shot" may actually consist of several joined together to create the illusion of appearing or disappearing. Look carefully at The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots (1895), one of the earlier trick films. A more thorough inspection reveals the moment where the physical shot with Mary's severed "head" begins, even though the entire film is conceptually one shot to the viewer.

The traditional "Gothic Novel" is, as Ian Watt describes it in The Rise of the Gothic Novel, an "oxymoron for 'Old-New'" in both substance and name. The Gothic style has been criticized, praised, accused of lacking real depth, and celebrated for the 'terrible sublime' aspect it seemed to invoke (Burke). Horace Walpole's The Castle of Otranto, the original "Gothic Novel," used ideas from both "ancient and modern" romances to create the proto-Gothic genre and a new method of literary expression. Walpole uses "old" theatrical elements and 'new' mimicry of nature in 'modern' novels to present what he calls "A Gothic Story" (Walpole 4). The Gothic genre draws on medieval gothic theatre, architecture, and traditions. Even at the time of its publication, the word "gothic" was used to describe various peoples, styles, and periods, often seen as archaic or unsophisticated compared to "modern" societal and literary "advancements." The combination of the theatrical "Gothic" and the novel's new format, which offers the reader a personal view of the characters' psychology, allows Gothic to persist and be both obsolete and new to readers far removed from the original writing.

A prominent gothic theme in Gothic novels is the concept of Chivalry. The medieval idea of chivalry, the training of a proper knight, is preserved and transformed in The Castle of Otranto. Chivalry is particularly important to Gothic writers because it represented the classic knight—brave, honorable, competent—and the perceived lack of such ideals in society, as seen by writers like Walpole. Through chivalric concepts and manners, the "gothic past" is idealized and romanticized (hinting at Gothic's evolution to Romantic) to try to improve the present. When Walpole wrote The Castle of Otranto, he was in politically troubled times and despaired over the future. Engaged in politics and facing (arguably) unfair accusations, he might have thought that the supposed morality and inherent "goodness" from the gothic era had been lost in the 'present' society. This concept is evident in characters like Frederic, who embodies many chivalric traits. Described as a prince who has suffered, affected by tragedy, and thought to have been killed by infidels, Frederic's portrayal includes many traditional chivalric images. The "gallant and courteous Knight" is exaggerated, introducing the Gothic trope of excess (66).

Supply chain management involves the flow of processes that move goods from the customer's order through raw materials, supply, production, and distribution to the customer. The term was coined in 1982 by consultant Keith Oliver, who described the comprehensive process of planning, implementing, and controlling activities within the supply chain to efficiently fulfill customer needs. The supply chain is made up of six key elements: production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information, which business managers use to deliver optimal customer service.

The first step in the supply chain is production, which is the foundation of the entire process. It involves determining when, why, where, and how everything will be produced. Managers need to understand customer desires, which can be gauged by analyzing the market, the primary indicator of customer demands. After understanding these demands, managers decide which products to produce and in what quantities. They determine the best location for production based on volume and quality while ensuring customer satisfaction. Once the site is chosen, managers focus on scheduling workloads and maintaining equipment. Every detail in production is critical, as any oversight can cost the company time and money. For instance, in my experience with Wal-Mart and Target, both companies have structured processes for every aspect of the business, from employee uniforms to receiving shipments. These processes allow the company to operate smoothly without confusion.

The second key element is supply, which involves strategic decisions about the core capabilities of a facility and the development of outsourcing partnerships. A company might have various production divisions for one product, each with different equipment, workers, and specialties. Managers must choose the division that best suits the product's processes. They might also outsource work to create speed, which is the ability to provide quality and flexibility while reducing or maintaining low costs.

Victorian novels are known for their rich detail and focus on the aristocracy of the era. However, two novels that are considered Victorian but diverge from this tradition are Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights. Both employ elements of mystery and a flair for the bizarre, which is atypical for novels of that period, thereby strengthening the characters in each work, offering insights that elaborate on their motives and emotions.

"And now, a host of bewildering and confusing ideas crowded his mind. He seemed to still be walking between Sikes and Crackit, who were angrily arguing, as their very words echoed in his ears; and when he caught his own attention, he realized he was speaking to them... Suddenly, he recoiled at the sound of gunfire; loud cries and shouts rose into the air; lights flashed before his eyes, and everything was noise and tumult, as an unseen hand hurriedly carried him away. Through all these rapid visions, there ran an undefined, uneasy awareness of pain, which wearied and tormented him incessantly." (Dickens, 220)

The two novels often utilize mystery through dream sequences or dreamlike states, although the content and function vary in each specific case. In Oliver Twist, these strange events often reveal insights into Oliver's inner layers, what pains him, and his awareness about the true nature of the things happening around him. When the shooting of Oliver is revisited in chapter 28, he vividly relives the event as if in a dream while struggling to find help. The passage emphasizes the lack of control Oliver had over the unfolding events, as well as the dire condition of his health, which was strongly present through his hallucinations of Sikes and Crackit. The shooting itself overwhelms him, all his senses are numbed as he does not notice the "unseen hand" that bears him away; he experiences his despair anew, detached from the shock of pain, as the pain is now constant and linked with fear rather than surprise. With Oliver being overwhelmed, the question arises about whose will brought about his misfortune, because it was certainly not his own. This shooting reinforces the notion that Oliver has little control over anything, as he cannot bring himself to even attempt to gain control of an event’s outcome, even when his life is in danger. A growing sense of defeat in Oliver is also implied by this section, as if old Fagin had begun to break him, forcing him into accepting this despair, affecting his ability to react. Otherwise, it can be assumed that Oliver would have made some effort, at least simply for the sake of his own life.

"The day passed – day! There was no day; it was gone as soon as it came – and night came on again; night so long, and yet so short; long in its dreadful silence and short in its fleeting hours."

A few years back, I worked in an after-school program tutoring elementary-aged students. I did my utmost to assist them in any subject where they were struggling, though my strengths were in English and reading. One of the instructors asked me to help a little boy named Adrian (I believe he was in third or fourth grade), who was having significant difficulties with reading. It struck me that something was amiss; he had the most peculiar issues. Some letters he could pronounce perfectly, while others he couldn't at all, it was the strangest thing. You see, he was of Latino descent, that much I was certain, yet the boy spoke perfect English. We continued to struggle until the day I met his mother. I was helping to watch over a few stragglers (for lack of a better word) while the rest of the after-school group was on a field trip when his mother walked in. She didn't speak a word of English, only Spanish. With my very poor Spanish (I was just learning), we managed to communicate. But then it hit me like a ton of bricks: Adrian could read well, he just wasn't very familiar with the English alphabet. I don’t know if that realization helped him much in the end, but I do hope he's doing better now.

I share this story to highlight the issue of language barriers in schools, particularly here in California. I also share it to show that it's not always as obvious as one might think. Even for a child who speaks perfect English, reading can still pose a major obstacle. I believe everyone can agree this problem exists, so what do we do? In Adrian's case, the solution was fairly straightforward: tutoring in English reading, especially focusing on the alphabet and pronunciation. But for the many children who barely speak English, the solution is much more complex. There isn't a single answer. The dual language system, mainstream immersion, private tutors, ESL classes—none of these alone will solve the problem. The key lies in combining all of these approaches!

Firstly, the dual language system is an excellent idea. Not only for children whose first language is Spanish, but for all children. "Children in two-way bilingual education programs have been found to outperform their peers academically." There is a lot of fear surrounding this idea, that it's a waste of resources, and that the majority of children in schools will not benefit. But that's incorrect. If we applied these programs as the norm in classrooms, rather than the exception, all children would benefit. How do we achieve this, though? Do we require all teachers to be bilingual? No. That would be unreasonable and somewhat unrealistic. However, I do think there’s no reason we can't have special aides, tutors, or whatever you want to call them, who are bilingual.

From the time we are children, most of us are told that there is something out there larger than we are, greater than we can comprehend. Some of us are sent to Sunday school to learn about it, while others go to the temple or search within themselves for answers. Many of us readily accept the religions handed down to us by our parents. However, some of us reject them completely, denying that there can be anything beyond our own personal egocentric universe. We may adopt one set of values only to later change our minds and embrace another. Whatever path we choose, we strive to define a part of ourselves through our unique perspectives on spirituality. We search for a light in the darkness to lead us out of the shadows and into the sun.

"A cardinal," my father said when I asked him what his favorite type of bird was. We sat on the porch of our house, listening to the rain pound on the tin roof above us as we smoked our cigarettes together. The gutters directed the rain down, drowning the plants along the edge of the porch. He looked out into the rain, the kind of gaze that seemed half searching, half remembering. Over the past few months, he had grown thinner, and his clothes hung limply from his body. His hair had thinned, more sparse than I remembered. He continued to stare into the rain, avoiding eye contact. I felt alone, afraid, and unable to talk to my father about how much I would miss him because discussing it would make it more real for both of us. I hugged him, sat back down, moved my chair a little closer to his, and joined him in gazing out into the falling rain of the June evening.

My father passed away in December of that year, five days after my twenty-second birthday. The chemo and radiation had not eased my father's suffering but merely kept him alive a few months beyond the doctors' predictions; what value there was in him suffering longer, I could not define. What kind of God would do this, I thought. Alone in the night, I said no prayers. If God existed, I thought, he had stopped listening to me long ago.

I had not wanted to watch him transition from this life into another. So I didn't. I couldn't watch the life that created me come to an end. I wanted to remember my father by how he lived, not how he died. Besides, I knew my father better than they did, better than his family, and knew Dad wouldn't want his only child to witness his death. I curled up in a ball in my bed for three days and waited for the news.

No one even called me.

John Taylor of Caroline was an early and passionate supporter of Republicanism. Though primarily a farmer, his career, along with a brief stint in politics, made him known for his dedication and candidness on issues of personal freedom and governance. His commitment to an agrarian system was foundational to almost all his governmental views. His efforts to preserve and promote what he deemed the superior profession colored his arguments on sovereignty, constitutionality, and even the judicial system.

Taylor believed the United States had a unique chance to create an ideal system, free from native tradition that could hinder government creators, thus enabling self-government. He was firm in his belief in the natural rights of man, viewing them as interconnected—if one right is denied, all fail, diminishing the value of those that remain. These rights should thus be out of governmental reach. He argued that the "state of nature" favored those with physical strength and malevolent intelligence but insisted this should not be true in a civilized society.

To build this ideal society, Taylor believed a government must account for man's inherent good and evil. He was very firm in his views on dualistic morality, stating that "as government is exercised by man, all its virtues and vices must be human" (ibid., p. 167). Good principles, as he defined them, protected private property, improved agriculture, and discouraged capitalism. He believed a government founded on such principles would function fairly, despite being inevitably led by greed and self-interest. Self-interest was, in his view, man's motivation in all things, considered evil only when it led beyond a society based on public good into sub-societies living at others' expense. A good government was essential to restrain man's natural evil, requiring careful oversight to prevent adding bad principles.

Taylor, like many staunch Republicans of his era, advocated for a strict interpretation of the Constitution. He desired a highly limited Federal government, with no more rights or powers than explicitly stated in the Constitution. He recognized that a large Federal government was costly and likely despotic. However, he also considered a simple, literal interpretation risky, as it could become corrupt without reference to the framers' intent. He viewed the Declaration of Independence as the true charter of the United States, explicitly describing the country as a group of sovereign states rather than a single nation.

I stared downward, my mind blankly processing the view before me. Without emotion, in silence, with a practiced awareness that observed but refused to connect the subject of study to any abstract understanding, my mind analyzed the scene before my eyes. Thoughts flowed into my mind and vanished again almost as quickly as they appeared. My consciousness worked so smoothly and cleanly that it seemed I had no real thoughts of my own, just an active and fluid experience of what I observed. 

Once, on the advice of an artist I worked with, I bought an art instruction book called "The New Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain." I had wanted to learn to draw since I was six years old, and this book teaches everything from understanding what a pencil is to the brain processes involved in interpreting lines. One technique the book teaches is to place a square frame around any picture the artist wants to study. This transforms an overwhelmingly detailed image, such as a bowl of fruit on a table in a kitchen connected to a dining room, into an easily comprehensible image, that bowl of fruit on a simple plane. 

At that moment, staring down at the bowl in front of me, I couldn't mentally project that artist's frame. I was so overwhelmed, so awed that I could only stand and gaze in amazement. Picasso went through his blue period, Monet loved greenery, and Italian Renaissance masters displayed a rainbow of colors. If I had any pretensions of presenting my perspective as artistically valuable, then before me were the beginnings of my picture, the start of my story, Work in Brown. 

Fingertips touched my chosen tool of artistry, muscles tensed and relaxed as my hand moved through space, my mind's will taking shape, which could have been the most creative moment of my life. Water swirled, serene and smooth, crystal clear and clean. Flakes of matter separated from the whole and were carried away into nothingness. Muscles tightened, jerked and spasmed a bit more quickly and anxiously the second time, my hand struck the handle of the toilet again. The offensive brown package refused to move, stuck like a slug at the bottom of the toilet. 

Mop loosely held in hand, feet set a foot apart, green tie uncomfortably knotted around my neck, I frowned slightly as I looked at the rude bundle of processed animal and plant matter that someone had left as a message for the fools who cleaned the bathrooms at Rite Aid. A few more flushes, a few more tranquil introspective moments to myself, then my hand moved towards the wall to my right, gripped the sheet at the end of the toilet paper, and began mummifying itself until it resembled an oven mitt. Standing up straight, then bending at the waist, my hand dipped slowly into the bowl, like a mother reaching into the oven for the Thanksgiving turkey...

Teenagers are dying behind the wheel. Several factors combine to create this deadly statistical vector for the youngest American drivers. The National Institutes of Health explain that one aspect of the problem is that the teenage brain is literally not ready for the dangers of driving. Simple inexperience is also at the heart of the problem. This inexperience not only leads to more fatal accidents but also to higher rates of vehicle rollovers, speeding, and running off the road. Teens also fare much worse when traveling with peers, which anyone with common sense knows they regularly do. The Southern California Injury Prevention Research Center conducted a study that showed the following correlation: between the age of the passenger and the number of traffic accidents that occur. California and other states have attempted to increase the safety of teen drivers by requiring provisional licenses that limit the hours teens may drive and prohibit other minors as passengers. But provisional driver's licenses are, in my opinion, merely stopgap measures. The real issue is that the youngest drivers, as a group, are simply not able to adequately handle the risks and responsibilities by all statistical measures. Psychologist Marvin Zuckerman believes even 18 is too young for a regular driver's license. USA Today reports that Zuckerman has conducted research suggesting that those under 19-20 often have a desire to take risks just for the thrill of it. It makes sense then to delay driving at least until the tendency to seek thrills decreases. If we continue to issue driver's licenses to young teens, not only will we continue to see deadly accidents, but the death toll is likely to reach staggering proportions in the coming years. By 2010, the children of Baby Boomers will be eligible to drive, and millions of new teen drivers will be ready to hit the road. Legislation dealing with this issue would be reasonably straightforward. Schools could continue to provide driver's education courses to begin the learning process for future drivers, but no one under the age of 18 should operate a motor vehicle. A provisional permit could still be issued before granting a full driver's license, and a certain number of practical driving hours would still be required as well. The specific number of hours required could be based on the number already required by most states (in California, for example, this number is currently 6 hours of behind-the-wheel training and 50 hours of practice with an adult). Because the deadly statistics for teen drivers come from a cross-section of all states, uniform national legislation on this issue would be a reasonable—and I believe effective—means of protecting teens across the nation. The legislation I suggest is by no means a novel idea.

This article addresses three aspects of Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD). First, it provides a brief definition of the disorder. Then, the diagnosis is explained, along with common traits or "red flags." Finally, the article concludes with ways a teacher in an inclusive classroom setting can support a student with CAPD.

Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD), also known as Auditory Processing Disorder (APD), refers to the efficiency with which the central nervous system (CNS) processes auditory information. Narrowly defined, (C)AP refers to the perceptual processing of auditory information in the CNS and the neurobiological activity supporting that processing, leading to electrophysiological auditory potentials (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). This means it is a disorder where the central nervous system (i.e., the brain) cannot correctly process what is heard. People with CAPD can hear normally and are thus not considered "hearing impaired"; instead, the brain area responsible for translating what we hear, separating words, or distinguishing conversations from background noise does not function as it typically should.

The earliest mention of the disorder, which became known as CAPD, dates back to the mid-1950s, referred to as "auditory imperception" (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005), when researchers were studying children with communication disorders. The Italian research team of Bocca, Calearo, and Cassinari began developing tests for these children in 1954; in 1961, Kimura introduced "dichotic testing and formulated a model to explain the physiology of the CANS underlying dichotic perception" (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). A national conference held in 1977 stimulated research on children with CAPD.

CAPD manifests in various ways: the affected person may not be able to localize or hear sounds in space; may struggle to discriminate between two or more "acoustic events" (sound occurrences); may not recognize sound patterns; may not differentiate changes in speech (like detecting sarcasm from a change in voice); one sound may be blocked by a subsequent sound; may lack the ability to synthesize sound cues (that is, interpret them in a meaningful way to act upon); and may not determine the sequence in which auditory information is presented (Ferre).

To diagnose CAPD, the patient must undergo "systematic observation of listening behavior and/or performance on tests of auditory function," which may be conducted by "audiologists, SLPs, psychologists, and others using various measures that evaluate auditory-related skills" (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). This may include questionnaires and surveys, as well as observing auditory behaviors, including how the patient responds to certain stimuli. Currently, no single tool or test is consistently used with a high diagnostic success rate, and there is no known cause for the disorder. Many tests present the patient with multiple simultaneous auditory stimuli and then ask them to differentiate certain elements, like a series of words or numbers. More advanced tests include recording acoustic signals within the ear and measuring responses to these signals.

While pursuing an education in social work, I aim to follow a career with the Division of Family and Children Services to assist children who have been abused or neglected and to support troubled families. The values I bring to the social work field include service, respect, ethical character, a commitment to improving relationships among others, and enhancing my professional skills to remain competent in my field. These core values are important not only to social workers but also to me personally.

I have always wanted to help others but was unsure of the career path I wanted to follow. Throughout my high school and college years, I saw many people deny their problems, and some used less than ideal coping mechanisms. Because of situations I witnessed, I chose to pursue a Bachelor’s degree in Psychology. Still uncertain about a career path, I decided to take a break after graduating from Piedmont College in 2009. One day that summer, I visited a friend who introduced me to a sixteen-year-old boy sitting nervously on her couch. She explained why he was visiting: to escape his abusive parents. The next day, I learned he had called the police to his parents’ home. To see if I could help, I drove to his parents’ house. Once there, I privately explained my concerns to the police and mentioned that I had just graduated with a degree in Psychology from Piedmont College. The police asked me to speak with the parents since the law could do nothing for the teenager. When I questioned the parents about the situation, they seemed nervous and used excuses to describe their son’s “manipulative” behavior in involving outside help for “simple” disputes. After this experience, I seriously began considering a career in social work to help children with “simple” family disputes.

Another important value for the field of social work is social justice. As a society, we claim that the individual is important, and we mourn those we have lost. The concept of the “individual” that society holds is more a follower of archaic traditions than actual uniqueness. So, if society mourns lost individuals, why do we strive to be like “everyone else?” I am an individual and do not enjoy limiting myself to be similar to others. Throughout my high school and college years, I protested against social injustice whenever I could: dyeing my hair unnatural colors, wearing clothes that matched my personality, piercing my ears beyond the traditional set, declaring my involvement with the GSBA (Gay Straight Bisexual Alliance), and fighting against racism and discrimination whenever I witnessed it, etc. I believe in social justice and will continue to protest against social injustice.

The text examines the biological and sociocultural models in relation to insomnia. The biological model emphasizes genetic information and health-related medical aspects. Sociocultural models focus on environmental relationships and their impact on race, ethnicity, demographics, and socioeconomic status. This review of insomnia examines these models and explains selected research to illustrate and clarify them. The research explanations and findings are critiqued for their strengths and weaknesses.

Sleep disorders can be classified as primary, related to another mental disorder, or linked to other issues. Primary sleep disorders include Dyssomnias and Parasomnias, while those related to another mental disorder connect to Axis I or Axis II disorders. Other sleep disorder categories may result from medical complications or substance use. Dyssomnias include Primary Insomnia, Primary Hypersomnia, Narcolepsy, Breathing-Related Sleep Disorder, Circadian Rhythm Sleep Disorder, and Dyssomnia Not Otherwise Specified. Primary Insomnia involves difficulty in adequate or maintained sleep, whereas Primary Hypersomnia entails trouble staying awake, lasting at least a month. Narcolepsy involves cataplexy and/or automatic REM. Dyssomnias focus on initiating and maintaining sleep, while Parasomnias involve behavioral and/or physiological abnormalities. Parasomnias include Nightmare Disorder, Sleep Terror Disorder, Sleepwalking Disorder, and Parasomnias Not Otherwise Specified. Sleep disorders related to another mental disorder involve difficulties due to Axis I (Clinical Disorders) or Axis II (Personality Disorders or Intellectual Disability). This review mainly focuses on insomnia and, to some extent, on primary sleep disorders in relation to the biological and sociocultural models.

The biological model of sleep disorders emphasizes genes, heritable factors, and physiological aspects. Orexin-containing neurons in the hypothalamus regulate sleep and wakefulness. Studies with mice found phenotypic GABAB receptors on orexin neurons responsible for sleep/wake states. GABAA receptor activation promotes sleep, whereas inhibiting it can reduce anxiety and induce sleep. The GABAB agonist (baclofen) was found to increase sleep time (Matsuki et al., 2009). These results suggest that mouse models can apply to human studies, indicating a genetic and environmental basis for human GABAB receptors. Issues or absence of this receptor could affect sleep quality without medication. If the phenotype is inherited, it could regulate sleep, and receptor changes could naturally disrupt sleep, impacting school, career, and everyday tasks requiring focus.

I have been a student at University Park for approximately two and a half years, or four and a half semesters. For many, including myself, navigating the campus can be an issue. During my freshman year, I lived in a dorm room in East Halls, which is practically the furthest eastern point of the campus, excluding the stadium and Bryce Jordan Center. Walking from my home in Stuart Hall to classes in far-off places like the Willard Building, near the campus center, could take up to 25 minutes on foot, especially when the weather was bad, as it often is in State College. In a conversation with an alum close to my age, I learned that not too long ago, the East Halls dorms were separated from the rest of the school by large areas of unused land. Today, that empty space is filled with sports fields, large new buildings, including the new Creamery and health services building, and surrounded by apartments. As our campus continues to expand, getting from one place to another becomes increasingly difficult. What is the best solution to the mobility problem? On a college campus, it's the bicycle. But a bike alone won't solve any problems. Students need to use them, and the campus should be designed to meet the needs of cyclists.

I was talking to a friend who recently resumed cycling after several years. He mentioned that he wondered why he ever stopped. "Bikes are great," he said, "for a few years it wasn't cool to ride a bike, but it's the only way to get around." Besides being good for your health, cycling is the most efficient way to travel. A bowl of oatmeal and some physical effort can take you 30 miles or more. Like many undergraduates, I now live off-campus; just as far from the center as some dorms. The smartest decision I made this year was to buy a bike. Every day, I have classes in the Thomas Building, which is easily a 25-minute walk from my home. Riding a bike can reduce that time to 5 minutes if I pedal fast enough. The only problem is, Pollock Road is the straightest path to the Thomas Building from my house, and it's not always easy to travel on, with or without a bike. Walking has its benefits too, but personally, I'm too busy to walk. If I didn't have my bike, walking would be my only reliable option to get to class. Walking to Thomas every day would add an extra 30-40 minutes to my day. That's over two and a half hours each week. Add to that all the other time I'd spend walking to and from other classes, appointments, etc. That's more time than I can spare.

Aldous Huxley criticizes the looming threat of technology and the capitalist structure, which is reinforced through the creation of a dystopia in his novel "Brave New World." The people value the community over the individual and are conditioned from the start to prioritize immediate happiness above all else. The citizens are revealed to be pawns in a larger game, confined to one ideology as dictated by the World Controller. When examining the work through the lens of Marxist theism, one can see the author's underlying suspicions regarding the development of these systems. Common Marxist terminology, such as homogeneity and reification, reinforces the idea that Huxley's novel comments on the flaws in the emerging economy of his time. Capitalism is satirized through the Marxist thesis of false consciousness. Essentially, the common people are prevented from knowing their true relations to other classes in economic terms, as they are mainly interested in their own gain. This is said to be the result of the ideological control of the proletariat and ordinary workers, something quite evident through the conditioning of the people in "Brave New World." The common classes, Delta, Gamma, etc., have no true will of their own; through hypnopaedia, the drive to consume, spend, and indulge is heightened above all else. This is manipulated, as previously mentioned, by the World Controller. Hegemony, the idea that groups of social classes are dominated by a separate group of individuals in totality, is clearly used in this case. The lower classes are completely unaware of the manipulation, quite literally 'buying into an ideology that supports that structure' (i.e., capitalism and consumerism). The upper classes are born with the ability to be aware of it but do nothing; few Alphas or Betas, apart from characters like Bernard, do more than simply accept their place. In fact, the interactions of the social classes, as will be discussed in greater length, are significant indications of the perceived oppression of capitalism. Relationships between different individuals do not exist in "Brave New World." The novel seemingly refuses to distinguish the characters – they are, even among major characters, lacking depth. Perhaps Huxley is suggesting that the rise of technology and capitalism together deprives man of free will and expression. Love does not exist, nor do the extremes of any one emotion; rather, interactions are kept superficial, distinctly portrayed through the men's remarks about women, primarily about their physical appearance (i.e., pneumatic quality), and the women's unabashed comments about their encounters, so to speak. Furthermore, each societal class's complacency with their status in the hierarchy indicates the socioeconomic effects of capitalism. Their absolute obedience in their role in the community is a reflection of Marxist thought on the proletariat, who are falsely assured of their own superiority over all else as long as they continue to consume, obey, and stay in line with the rest of their peers.

Almost four years ago, I attended a course on Islam at CBC. One of the primary topics of intense discussion in the class was whether Islam is a hostile religion. I think this question is more relevant today than ever. Looking back at the events since 9/11, I've personally seen the mass media transition from a hostile perspective on Islam and extremists to a strong tolerance for Islam in America. I don't believe in 2001 we could have had a presidential candidate named Barack Obama, who has evident Muslim roots in his family. The Prophet's biography fascinates me because, based on what I know of Muhammad's history, it contradicts his personality. From what I previously learned, I thought Muhammad forced conversions to Islam, conquering tribes and compelling them to adopt Islam. However, according to the biography, Muhammad is depicted as a martyr, misunderstood, who even humbled himself before others. Subsequently, people came one by one to recognize the 'truth' in his teachings and sought him out. There are also striking similarities between the works of Jesus and the 'miracles' of Muhammad. The most evident is when he took mutton and milk and multiplied it to be more than enough for forty men. This writing style suggests to me that the authors wanted Muhammad to be seen as the humble prophet who needed to prove nothing but lived in truth and miracles. This kind of fallacy is troubling because it undermines the miracle and life of Jesus Christ. To me, it feels like they are trying to steal and claim credit for Jesus' life and essence through Muhammad. There are also numerous stories in the biography aiming to provide evidence of 'witness' or self-initiated conversions to Islam. But the issue is that many stories are from a third-party perspective. The author notes hearing from someone who heard from another, etc. I didn't appreciate this because, although intended to validate the stories, I felt it diminished them and made them more suspicious. What bothers me most about this work is their attempt to elevate Muhammad as a godly man who was humble, endearing, wise, and gentle. But history contradicts the notion of Muhammad being gentle and humble, and I can't help but wonder if Muslims today understand the true history behind Muhammad's rise to power.

The teachings of Jesus and the beliefs he held during his lifetime were quickly set aside in the development of Christian thought that advanced after his life. If we look at this history broadly, we notice a trend of Christianity drifting further and further from its origins. Today's world seems to show an increasing awareness and an unprecedented progressive tendency. While traditional people remain and resist any kind of thinking beyond what they were taught, this portion of the population may not be influential enough to affect the whole. Among Christians, historical awareness will grow significantly in the coming years. A desire will spread to differentiate the doctrines added over time to Christianity from the actual intent of the religion's namesake. It might take decades or even centuries, but the outcome will be inevitable: There will be a major reversal in the trend of Christian history. There will be a progression back to its original form. A movement will grow numerically, removing layers of doctrine as if the clock were turning backward, until nothing remains except a concept of what Jesus introduced to humanity on behalf of God before any other thinkers made such claims. When this trend sweeps through the United States and Europe, influencing masses in its wake to worship as if living in the time of Jesus, following only his ideas, the church as an institution will remain strong to lead the way. However, because the theological clock will have moved backward, the extreme diversity in Christendom will turn into increasing uniformity of belief and practice. Between regions, denominations, and divisions of all kinds, we will see increasing similarities instead of differences. Human history is filled with great reversions. One example is how Christians were once persecuted, shunned, and killed by the Roman Empire, but later that empire became a Christian institution. Our nation has moved from African-American slavery to African-American leadership. The great reversion coming in our future will play out in the realm of the Christian religion, undoing history in search of the source and undoing diversity in the process. It is crucial to note that part of what will make this process possible will be a method of reading Jesus' words metaphorically, not as literal statements. So, what has happened since Jesus' lifetime? If we look far enough back into history, we find only Judaism, the theological beginning of the Christian religion. Monotheism, the perception of a divinely revealed religion, and the authority of the Hebrew scriptures were all at the core of the religion by the time the Romans took control of Jerusalem in 63 B.C.E. The Jewish population did not share one spirit. They divided into Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots, and a majority of common people.

I believe that "The Jungle" reveals how humans are inherently greedy and self-centered. They focus primarily on improving their own lives and ignore those below them. This is depicted in many ways throughout the book. The most obvious example is the behavior of the owners and managers of large factories. Their main goal is to make their businesses as large and profitable as possible, with no regard for anyone or anything that stands in their way or is harmed by their progress.
