Upton Sinclair describes it as: "The line of buildings stood clear-cut and black against the sky; here and there out of the mass rose the great chimneys, with the river of smoke streaming away to the end of the world." Sinclair illustrates the great harm caused by this pollution, emphasizing that the owners have no regard for anyone or anything that might be hurt. They don't care about the massive smoke plumes from the factories or the animal waste runoff from the numerous pens around Packingtown.

The owners and managers also disregarded their employees, who worked to make them rich. They would do anything to make or save an extra dollar, "So from top to bottom the place is simply a seething cauldron of jealousies and hatreds; there is no loyalty or decency anywhere about it, there is no place in it where a man counted for anything against a dollar." They forced their employees to work long, grueling hours and could lay off many people without warning, without any compensation or help finding new jobs. During the era "The Jungle" is set in, there were few, if any, laws or regulations to protect workers' safety or well-being. This allowed managers and owners to act freely, pushing their employees to speed up production and work in terrible conditions. Although the book doesn't say it directly, those who lived and worked to exhaustion in Packingtown were expected to endure the harsh conditions both at work and in their living environments. There were no agencies or organizations to provide information or assistance to workers. While unions existed, they often did more harm than good, profiting from the poor workers. The workers were treated so badly and trapped in the Packingtown system that they were described as slaves: "Here is a population, low-class and mostly foreign, hanging always on the verge of starvation and dependent for its opportunities of life upon the whim of men every bit as brutal and unscrupulous as the old-time slave drivers; under such circumstances, immorality is exactly as inevitable, and as prevalent, as it is under the system of chattel slavery."

Dream-land is one of Edgar Allan Poe’s self-proclaimed better poems. In "Dream-Land," Poe uses the term "Thule" in lines 6 and 56, which Mabbott traces back to Virgil. Virgil used the term to refer to an island north of Britain, which the Greeks considered the edge of the known world. It is certain that Virgil used the term, but there is a more recent source that deserves some credit. Poe was very interested in German authors. This quote is important because it shows Poe's familiarity with Goethe’s writings. Karl J. Arndt, in his book Poe’s Politian and Goethe’s Mignon, comments on the similarity of their two poems, concluding that Poe imitated Goethe. The Oxford Companion to English Literature states that Goethe was a celebrated writer of the poetic drama Faust, published in two parts, the first in 1808 and the second in the year of Goethe’s death, 1832. Within the poetic verse of Faust’s second part is a short poem titled "The King of Thule." The poem is about a king whose wife dies after giving him the gift of a goblet. After her death, he begins to drink heavily and cry from the memory of his dead queen. He then decides it is his time to die and leaves his possessions to his children, except for the goblet. He walks to a cliff, throws the goblet into the sea, closes his eyes, and dies. The demeanor of the King of Thule and the description of the king in Dream-Land are very similar, perhaps a dark counterpart to Poe’s loss and reliance on drinking. Faust was also turned into a romantic drama by H P Grattan in 1842, less than a year before Poe used the term Thule in "The Pit and the Pendulum." Poe references Thule twice in his collected writings. Once, Poe references "ultima Thule" in The Pit and the Pendulum, but he uses this phrase in "Dream-Land" twice, as bookends for the poem. "The King of Thule" and "Dream-Land" can be read as companion pieces. In "Dream-Land," the speaker describes the landscape of Thule as dark and lonely, haunted by dead friends, and sees a shadowy world without color. All of these scenes could be read into Goethe’s "The King of Thule" as he has just lost his wife, is lonely, and has lost his will to rule or even live. The entire poem is a description as though the speaker has stepped into Goethe’s poem. Goethe was a significant author whom Poe would have known, if for no other reason than his respect for Tennyson. Poe had this to say when asked if he admired Tennyson. Aside from the connection to Tennyson, Poe would have been exposed to Goethe’s work through the many reproductions that were taking place after the original publication.

Under California law, a customer injured after slipping on an applesauce spill in a grocery store could potentially be awarded punitive damages by showing that the store manager acted with malice. This could be argued if the manager had been informed twice of the spill and neglected to clean it for half an hour because he was having dinner. A judge is unlikely to summarily dismiss Jennifer Palmer's claim for punitive damages. To justify such a claim, the plaintiff must provide evidence that the defendant's actions were carried out with a willful and conscious disregard for the likely harm resulting from the conduct, and also show that the conduct was despicable. Palmer can argue that Martin should have known the probable harm of not cleaning up a spill, as several D&D customers had been injured from slipping in the months before Palmer’s incident; despite this knowledge, he still failed to have the spill cleaned. Palmer's argument that Martin's actions were despicable is less convincing, but still reasonable given that six slip-and-fall incidents occurred in 2009, yet Martin did not take appropriate actions to ensure the safety of his store. On October 13, 2009, at 5:00 pm, Rich Wayne, an employee of D&D Markets, informed his manager, Paul Martin, about an applesauce spill in an aisle. Martin told Wayne he was on a dinner break and "didn't have time to deal with customer complaints." At 5:15 pm, another employee, Mary J. Haddigan, also informed Mr. Martin of the spill, and Martin responded in the same way. At 5:30 pm on the thirteenth, the plaintiff, Jennifer Palmer, slipped on the spill and sustained a serious back injury. Prior to Palmer’s accident, five different slip-and-fall incidents were reported at D&D in 2009. Palmer is now suing D&D for compensatory and punitive damages related to her injury, and we are considering filing a motion for partial summary judgment against the punitive damage claim. In California, a plaintiff can recover punitive damages for a breach of an obligation not arising from a contract if the defendant acted with "oppression, fraud, or malice." Cal. Civ. Code, § 3294(a) (Lexis 2010). The statute defines malice as conduct intended to cause harm, or in the absence of intent, the conduct must be "despicable" and carried out with "a willful and conscious disregard of the rights or safety of others." Id. at § (c)(1). Courts have characterized conduct as malicious when committed with a conscious disregard for the plaintiff's rights if the defendant "was aware of the probable dangerous consequences of his conduct, and willfully and deliberately failed to avoid those consequences." Taylor v. Super. Ct. of Los Angeles Co., 598 P. 2d 853, 856 (Cal. 1979).

She had always felt like she needed something. There was this desire that refused to be satisfied. It began when she was about 14, just entering her teenage years. And it was still there 3 years later, at the age of 17. By then, she had realized she wanted someone rather than something. Yet, she felt no interest in any boys. Some had been drawn to her, going through awkward attempts to win over the unapproachable, but none appealed to her. She often questioned herself about this strange feeling, trying to understand what could cause such an unusual situation for a teenage girl. Years of contemplation led to theories, but nothing substantial enough for her to ponder deeply. So she lived her life, constantly questioning her desires.

A day at home was usually peaceful. Her parents were good and calm people. They never argued with each other, and strangely enough, arguments with their daughter were rare. The only disputes they had were about her asserting her independence and free spirit. She was the daughter of a very calm couple, but she certainly countered their energies with her vibrant and fun personality, which made her very likable, along with the fact that she was a kind person.

Today, however, was not a calm day. As she moved from room to room, looking for new inspiration for herself, she heard a short scream from the kitchen, the sound of her mother's beautiful voice. She rushed into the room, beginning to panic as she frantically asked, "Mom?! Mom, what's wrong?!" She saw her mother lying on the floor, appearing to be in pain as she kept saying "Ow" in short breaths. The daughter ran to her side and put a hand on her to offer help. "Ouch ... swee - ty, I ... need you to take me to - the hospital." The words were rushed and strained, and her daughter could tell she was in immense pain. "Okay Mom, just tell me where I can pick you up." Her mother gestured with her hands, and at that moment, the household hero was very grateful she had taken strength classes. She carried her mother to the car, laid her down in the back, and drove.

A visit to the hospital brought the smell of disinfectant and illness, mixed with fear. But she didn't notice it, as her mind was too focused on helping her mother. She quickly carried the injured woman inside and started calling for help from the doctors. A few worried faces gathered around, and someone quickly brought a rolling bed and laid her mother on it. They took her for immediate examination, and her daughter was left to sit and worry.

Her mother had fallen off a stepping stool while trying to reach a vase from the highest cabinet they had.

This study aimed to demonstrate that following a "Mediterranean Diet" (Med diet), as reflected by a high "alternate Mediterranean (aMed) diet score," is linked to a reduced risk of chronic heart disease (CHD), stroke, and stroke mortality. The aMed diet is a modified version of the Med diet, emphasizing higher intake of plant foods, including plant proteins (excluding potatoes but including fruits, nuts, whole grains, and legumes), monounsaturated fats (compared to saturated fats), and fish, with reduced consumption of animal products and saturated fats. Moderate alcohol consumption is allowed.

Previous prospective studies documented an inverse relationship between following a Med diet and the risk of total and cardiovascular (CVD) mortality. An intervention trial showed the Med diet to be more effective than a low-fat diet for promoting weight loss and lowering the ratio of total to high-density lipoprotein cholesterol in obese individuals. Earlier studies did not focus on stroke or stroke mortality.

This epidemiological study followed 74,886 women, aged 38 to 63, without a history of CVD or diabetes, who participated in the Nurses' Health Study, a cohort study of 121,700 female nurses across 11 US states. From 1984 to 2004, the authors calculated an aMed diet score six times from self-reported "food frequency questionnaires" (FFQs) designed to assess nutrient intake in the prior year. More than 95% of nurses continued participating throughout the 20-year period. FFQs underwent validation studies. Reports of CHD, fatal CHD, and stroke were confirmed through medical or hospital records, autopsies, or death certificates. Where records were unavailable, cases were considered "probable" and included, with about 17% of all strokes and 24% of nonfatal myocardial infarctions classified this way. Body mass index, smoking status, aspirin use, multivitamin intake, menopausal status, and postmenopausal hormone use were calculated for each FFQ, and from 1986 onward, leisure-time physical activity was assessed.

To reduce random variation and better represent long-term dietary intake, cumulative averages of the aMed score from repeated FFQs were calculated (averaging scores from two previous years). Adjustments were made for "confounders" (factors that could affect results) by accounting for age, smoking, BMI, menopausal status, postmenopausal hormone use, multivitamin intake, alcohol intake, physical activity, and aspirin use.

Cox proportional-hazard modeling was used to assess the association between an aMed score and the risk of CHD and stroke, using separate models for fatal and nonfatal CHD and stroke types.

Greater adherence to the Mediterranean diet, as indicated by a higher aMed diet score, was associated with a lower risk of incident CHD and stroke in women. During 20 years of follow-up, 2,391 incident cases of CHD, 1,763 incident cases of stroke, and 1,077 cardiovascular disease deaths (fatal CHD and strokes combined) were observed. Women in the highest aMed quintile had a lower risk of both CHD and stroke compared to those in the lowest quintile (relative risk [RR], 0.71).

Hitler is alive in Burma, the sign reads.

Ellen Page, star of Juno, stands alone on a street corner holding a piece of cardboard above her head, with the unsettling message scrawled onto her sign with a Sharpie. Burma, also known as Myanmar, is a Southeast Asian country ruled by a tyrannical military junta that came to power in 1962 through a coup d’état. In 2007, several street protests occurred, marking the first public demonstrations in a decade. Led by a large number of Burmese monks, these protests were called "The Saffron Revolution," named after the color of the monks' robes. After the initial uprisings, the general public began to take an interest in the protests, and while the Burmese government initially grudgingly allowed the monks to participate in peaceful gatherings, the violence soon escalated into what some considered an all-out war between the monks and the military junta, with the military actively invading and looting monasteries across the country. Foreign journalists were rounded up and imprisoned on the spot, with a Japanese photojournalist named Kenji Nagai killed on September 27, 2007, just for being present at a street protest. While the official death toll is listed at 13 killed, Colonel Hla Win, who defected from the army days before the official report, is quoted as saying, "Many more people have been killed in recent days than you have heard about. The bodies can be counted in several thousand."

This is nothing new. While these are some of the most recent examples of atrocities occurring in our world, a government's desire to suppress dissent and maintain complete control over its citizens has existed for as long as civilization itself. Early Roman emperors declared themselves chosen by the gods to have complete executive authority over every aspect of their society. Japanese emperors are believed to actually be gods, sent to our world to lead their people to prosperity through the invention of Motorola cell phones and hara-kiri, and our current president, George W. Bush, holds weekly conference calls with Ted Haggard, the leader of Stupid People Worldwide, a subsidiary group of the Republican Party.

Some of the most well-known examples of such actions include incidents like the June 4, 1989 protest at Tiananmen Square, where intellectuals, labor activists, and students gathered to protest the authoritarian rule of the government. The death toll in that particular instance varies widely, with official reports from the Chinese government stating 200-300 dead, to reports from the Chinese Red Cross declaring between 2,000-3,000 dead. Another is the Rwandan genocide of the 1990s, where Hutu militia groups, aided by the Rwandan government, began a systematic killing of all Tutsis, as well as political moderates, regardless of their ethnic backgrounds. Hitler's "Third Reich," a period spanning several years and countries where anyone of Jewish background was rounded up and killed, is another extreme example.

Duke Ellington's impact on jazz largely comes from his long career and his creative ability to mold his orchestra. While his presence on the piano is often subtle in many of the compositions chosen for this task, Ellington excelled as a composer in creating rich and complex pieces that highlighted the individual talents of his band members. He designed a framework allowing soloists to freely improvise and wrote tightly orchestrated pieces and phrases that utilized the unique styles of band members to emphasize musical ideas. In doing so, he also generally accentuated the orchestra's tone, crafting coherent and original sounds to fit each piece. Ellington's mastery of the sound of individual players and their fit within an evolving ensemble allowed him to compose some of the most innovative and brilliant works in jazz history.

The Grove Music Dictionary, in discussing Ellington's sound and innovation, cites Creole Love Call as an example of using the voice "as a jazz instrument" throughout his career. This is an early example of Ellington's use of voice to add texture and color without the constraint of lyrics. Creole Love Call also showcases Ellington's ability to complement the style of his soloists, a skill evident throughout his career. This slow, deliberate twelve-bar blues piece includes six choruses:

Chorus 1: Call and response between voice and reeds, with the voice starting smooth and melodic, then shifting to a rougher sound towards the end.

Chorus 2: A muted trumpet solo elaborating on the basic melody and emphasizing several extended blue notes.

Chorus 3: A sweeping clarinet solo in a high register, supported by a subtle syncopated piano phrase.

Chorus 4: The full band echoes the first chorus with call and response by the brass and reed sections.

Chorus 5: The climactic chorus, as the reeds begin the call and response in a high register, backed by syncopated stop-time from the brass and rhythm sections.

Chorus 6: A return to the structure of the first chorus, featuring call and response between voice and reeds, with the voice employing the "growl" technique, soloing as an instrument.

Tag: A brief tag with a vocal run and a dissonant novelty ending by a trombone.

Ellington's use of voice to add a tonal dimension to this piece is an example of a stylistic trait that permeates his work.

In Hot and Bothered, recorded a year later, Ellington combines his skill in tight orchestration with his ear for tone color. A call and response phrase between "Bubber" Miley on muted trumpet and Baby Cox’s scat singing uses the vocal elements of Miley's playing and the instrumental qualities of Cox's voice to create a rich and complementary sound. It Don’t Mean a Thing (If It Ain’t Got That Swing) extends these ideas, as Ellington skillfully employs Joe “Tricky Sam” Nanton, a mainstay in Ellington's orchestra, to introduce the melody on muted trombone.

Why do organisms evolve in the way they do? Are there limitations or constraints that influence the direction of evolutionary change? Even though in 1917, D'Arcy Thompson stated that "even now the zoologist has scarcely begun to dream of defining even the simplest organic forms in mathematical language," the same can be said today. Recently, mathematical modeling has been applied to general aspects of mollusk skeletogenesis through both ontogeny and phylogeny (e.g., Raup and Stanley, 1981). Our study explores how mathematical modeling of ontogenetic and phylogenetic changes in Prunum, together with experimental studies, can be used to illuminate the mechanisms involved in the direction and magnitude of evolutionary-developmental changes. We used X-ray images of Prunum species to outline quantitative parameters that could be used to model hypothetical and actual skeletal morphologies. These parameters were input into the software program CerioShell (Stone, 1995). We modeled hypothetical shell morphologies that could interpret the boundaries of possible morphological changes in Prunum. These results are being combined with experimental and descriptive studies to better understand macroevolutionary events in this clade.

A shell can be considered as a structure that is a tube traveling over time through 360 degrees of space. These turns or coils of a spiraled shell are called whorls, which are seen as spiraling around an imaginary central axis. This axis runs through the central column of the shell and is known as the columella. The speed at which the whorls enlarge can vary, and a continuous line separates each whorl, known as a suture. In most shells, the largest whorl is the last whorl (body whorl). The spire is considered to be all the whorls except the last. The apex is the tip of the spire, and the opposite end is referred to as the base. The animal extends out of its shell through an opening called the aperture.

Shells can be viewed in apical, basal, apertural, and abapertural views. (The "usual" orientation of a shell is an apertural view, with the aperture facing the viewer and the apex pointing upwards.)

A method for counting whorls is described below. First, the shell should be viewed from the apical view and then it should be determined where the first suture begins. A line can then be drawn dividing the shell into two parts. Whorls are counted from this line and estimated to a quarter of a whorl.

A shell can be seen as a series of apertures traveling through space and time as the animal builds its shell. It is possible to trace the path of the aperture via the coordinates of the center of each whorl’s aperture as well as the horizontal and vertical radius of the aperture.

This trajectory can be graphically and mathematically represented. Once a mathematical formulation is established, it is possible to vary parameters and modify the mollusk's skeletogenesis.

The rate of neonatal and infant mortality in Indonesia has remained relatively stable over the past decade. While the country is on track to achieve many of the Millennium Development Goals, such as those for water and sanitation, progress in child and maternal health is unfortunately far from the improvements needed to meet the target goals by 2015. The various reasons for these shortcomings are discussed below, indicating a need to strengthen the health system rather than focus on programmatic interventions.

Indonesia has made progress in the number of births attended by a skilled health worker, with 72% of births now meeting this target. However, this category still includes traditional workers, such as midwives, who cannot perform medical interventions in complicated pregnancies (hence the high percentage of maternal deaths due to hemorrhage). In other words, the improvements made in this particular indicator are somewhat misleading, and much work remains. Additionally, there has been a decline in the percentage of diarrheal cases in children under five treated by a health professional. Although data on postnatal care is incomplete, it is clear that this area is also concerning, with low rates across the country.

Cesarean-section rates are still lower than expected, around 4%. The cesarean rates also point to another concerning issue. While the cesarean rate is 7% in urban areas, it is only 2% in rural areas. This highlights the problem of equity in coverage across the country. Clearly, access to healthcare services is concentrated around urban areas. Another access issue concerns vertical equity. There is a 27% gap in service utilization between the poorest and richest quintiles. Clearly, the poor are finding it much more difficult to access healthcare services, likely due to out-of-pocket costs.

When discussing the next steps to improve neonatal and maternal care indicators, the basic question is how to most effectively address the lack of services. Specifically, should Indonesia develop program-specific approaches or strengthen the overall health system without focusing on pre- and post-pregnancy care for the mother and child? There is no doubt that programmatic approaches to solve the problems outlined above are attractive. "Vertical approaches," which target one sector of improvements, not only have much more targeted, manageable objectives but also generally produce faster results. However, there are some drawbacks to consider. One major drawback is that investing heavily in programming for a particular area of the health sector often means that funding for other areas suffers and human resources will flock to the area with more resources (the effect of international funding on HIV/AIDS and its effect on the family planning sector is one example). Additionally, operating multiple parallel programs for one area results in duplication of services that are also uncoordinated between programs. This leads to an increase in forms and paperwork for supplies and funding.

The classification of popular music has expanded over the past century to include such an array of genres that listing them all definitively is challenging. To add complexity, nearly all genres—like rap, rock, country, jazz, and folk, to name a few—have spawned numerous sub-genres and sub-sub-genres. Arguably, the sub-genre of heavy metal rock has become one of the most diverse and expressive genres in popular music in the last 40 years. It's expressive as it showcases a wide range of emotions, often leaning towards the darker end of the spectrum. It's diverse because soon after the genre began, people noticed its flexibility and began creating their own sub-genres, followed by sub-sub-genres, continuing this chain to the present day.

Today, in the heavy metal movement, there are so many niche groups that it’s difficult to define what heavy metal exactly is. It has grown to incorporate numerous themes from other genres, yet, like everything, it originated from somewhere. To truly understand today’s metal music, one must first grasp what the metal movement is and why it’s more than just a genre.

Metal is, in many ways, a movement defined by darkness. It can be seen as "music of more"—more bass, more volume, more intensity, more theatricality. Less primitiveness, more skill; metal musicians are adept with their instruments, and this is evident in their music. Metal is also a movement heavily influenced by drugs, with the psychedelic drug boom in the mid-70s leading people to create wild, otherworldly records, using drugs as an excuse for their creativity. It possesses many dark, visceral qualities, a novelty in the music scene compared to popular music that lacked such dark emotional elements. Later metal generations have also drawn influence from the dark, visceral qualities of the Romantic Era. Lyrics from "Helter Skelter" by The Beatles reflect the darkness central to the movement.

These lyrics from "Helter Skelter" reveal The Beatles' darker side. They show the ups and downs, supposedly influenced by drugs. Some consider this song one of the first heavy metal tracks. It was a response to a Rolling Stones song that also had a heavier, darker tone. The Beatles aimed to prove they could be as heavy as the Stones, thus including it on The White Album.

A few decades before Surrealist artists started creating their dreamlike paintings, Henri Rousseau was meticulously shaping his own dreams, both literally and metaphorically. His 1910 painting, The Dream, by the renowned Post-Impressionist artist, depicts not only a woman marveling at the wonders of a land she visits in a dream but also reflects Rousseau's personal dreams and ambitions as a painter. From the start of his career, he longed for recognition, acceptance, and praise from fellow artists and art enthusiasts, yet he found himself facing a challenging internal dilemma to realize this aspiration. The Dream is Rousseau's work that best encapsulates his lifelong inner struggle: whether to adopt or imitate certain painting styles to gain acceptance from the critical art world he so admired, or to grant himself the freedom to be creatively independent and unique, forging his own path.

To analyze The Dream from this perspective, one must first be somewhat familiar with Rousseau's life story. Born on May 21, 1844, in the town of Laval in northwestern France, Henri Rousseau's father was a tinsmith and hardware dealer who "enjoyed bourgeois prosperity" (Shattuck 47). Rousseau received no formal artistic training; instead, he worked until the age of forty for France as a gabelou, an employee of the municipal toll service, despite being mistakenly nicknamed douanier, a customs inspector (Shattuck 46). The death of his first wife, Clémence, following the deaths of eight infant children, left Rousseau with only one child, a daughter named Julia, and immense grief (Shattuck 49). Consequently, he sought solace in a new life and turned to painting to find comfort and new beginnings. Unlike his contemporaries who sentimentalized and romanticized the peasant in their paintings, Rousseau was essentially a folk artist with the hopes and dreams of an average member of his class.

Rousseau's obsession with being accepted by the art world is somewhat understandable when evaluated in context: as discussed, not only was he untrained in formal painting and began his career at a much older age, but he was also creating works alongside many other talented and more well-known modern artists. Although he had been working for many years, Rousseau only started to gain proper recognition for his art around the same time Matisse was establishing his reputation as an artist. In the book Modern French Painters, author Jan Gordon asserts that while technically competitors in the art scene, the two differed not only in style and subject but also in their reasons for painting: "Matisse was a painter who feared painting in a trite way, whereas Rousseau's desire was to create a picture so conventional that he would be admitted to the Artiste Français" (92).

Many great thinkers have suggested a close link between ethics and aesthetics, between truth and beauty. I believe there is a fundamental reason for this. As John Keats states in "Ode on a Grecian Urn," "Beauty is truth, truth beauty—that is all / Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know." Much of what we know in life is learned through education or experience. However, as Keats implies, we seem to appreciate ethics and aesthetics without being taught in these expected ways. Both ethics and aesthetics aim to describe rather than prescribe. Our studies of morality and beauty are largely attempts to explain why a piece of art or literature is beautiful, or why an action is moral, rather than providing a set of rules for judging or creating good art or moral behavior.

Criticism of art or morals can never fully capture what is good or beautiful. A discussion about the value of da Vinci's Mona Lisa might focus on concepts like foreground, background, contrast, or cultural context, but ultimately these do not explain why it is good art. Instead, when asked about a favorite work of art or literature, it is common to hear a phrase like "There's just something about it" before a more complex or critical explanation. I believe that neither art nor morals can be completely reduced to a description of their qualities. As Flannery O'Connor says, "A story is a way to say something that can't be said any other way... you tell a story because a statement would be inadequate." No matter how completely we describe the properties of a literary work, something transcendent remains. I believe ethics shares this quality. As Wittgenstein says, "It is clear that ethics cannot be expressed. / Ethics is transcendental." I suggest that it is this "something," this je ne sais quoi, which is the most powerful attribute of art and morality, and that this transcendental nature of both ethics and aesthetics provides a connection point between them.

I believe that morality and art are closely related because we experience both most powerfully at a noumenal level, to use a Kantian term. They impact us at a level that can be experienced but not fully explained. This link is even stronger when it comes to the art of literature. As McKean says, "What most distinguishes literature from the other arts, what is truly unique about the art, is its moral quality. It may be that moral standards are inappropriate to other arts, such as music, but they seem to be as relevant to literature as they are to life itself. Living necessarily involves values. . . . Literature is important to us precisely because of the values we find there."

Modern Germany is seen as a powerful force, a nation united by its unique cultural blend that stretches from the shadows of the Alps in Munich to the Baltic Sea city of Kiel. This culture can be experienced from Cologne on the Rhine, through Germany's center, to the Saxon city of Dresden on the Elbe. Given such a distinct culture, it is not surprising that Germany, as we know it today, originates from many different sources and tribes.

Germania is the ancestral land of the Germans. The name's origins are highly debated among scholars and historians. Tacitus claimed that the name came from a Germanic tribe known as the Tungrians, who were previously known as Germans before crossing the Rhine to fight the Gaulish forces (Tacitus, 98). Julius Caesar first used the term "Germanus" in his commentary on the Gallic Wars, where he subdued the Gauls and fought with Germanic tribes that often crossed the Rhine under dubious pretenses. He borrowed this word from the Gauls themselves to distinguish between those he had conquered (the Gauls) and those he had not. While the origin is uncertain, some believe it referred to a neighbor in the Gaulish language. In the first chapter of his first book on these wars, Julius Caesar notes: "Germans, who dwell beyond the Rhine, with whom they (the Gauls) are continually waging war... They engage in almost daily battles with the Germans." (Julius Caesar, 50-40 BC) Others suggest the meaning comes from the spear they used in warfare, known as a "ger" (O.E.D, 2010), or perhaps from the Old Irish word "garim" meaning "to shout," indicating the Germans were loud or noisy. (Names of Germany)

The early Roman historian Tacitus, in his AD 98 writing “De Origine et situ Germanorum,” which described the origins of the Germans, noted that “I should regard (the Germans) as aboriginal, and not mixed at all with other races through immigration or intercourse. For, in former times it was not by land but on shipboard that those who sought to emigrate would arrive... Who would leave Asia, or Africa, for Italy for Germany, with its wild country, its inclement skies, its sullen manners and aspect, unless indeed it were his home?(SIC)” (Tacitus, 98)

And who would leave Rome for Germania? Certainly not the Romans, at least not yet. They would send their conquests into the lands of Germania for goods and occasionally lead a land campaign, but in the end, they mostly returned home to their expansive empire. As the Germanic tribes began to appear in the middle of the first century, they lived on the borders of the Roman Empire, trading goods taken from the land and offering their skills by serving in the ranks of the Roman army (Ozment, 2005, pg. 17).

The play "Twelfth Night" conveys that while disguises can effectively sustain prolonged deception, in the end, a person must discard the false identity or risk losing themselves. A challenge in ending deception is the potential for feeling alienated. Thus, one must decide between self-preservation or preserving relationships with others. Some might respond neutrally to being deceived, but others might find it offensive.

Deception in gender role reversal is particularly complex, raising questions such as why someone feels the need to adopt a disguise of the opposite gender. In Viola's case, her actions are a form of self-protection: “I’ll bring you to a captain in this town/ Where lie my maiden weeds, by whose gentle help/ I was preserved to serve this noble count…” (5.1.247-249).

Upon arriving in a foreign land, Viola pretends to be a man for safety. Her plan succeeds but isolates her from women, depriving her of support. Complicating matters, she is so convincing that Olivia mistakes her for Sebastian and falls in love: “Whither, my lord? Cesario, husband, stay.” (5.1.138). Viola also faces repressed romantic feelings with Orsino: “Boy, thou hast said to me a thousand times/ Thou never shouldst love woman like to me.” (5.1.260-261).

To modern readers, "Twelfth Night" may illustrate how deception reveals hidden emotions, especially for Olivia and Orsino. Certain passages suggest they might have unspoken desires that Viola/Cesario's presence forces them to confront. For example, is Olivia attracted to Cesario because he seems male, or does she secretly harbor feelings for women? It's likely not the case, as Olivia seems to parody those who judge others based on looks.

This is evidenced by Olivia's easy transition of affection from Cesario to Sebastian, viewing Cesario/Viola as family, not a romantic interest: “A sister, you are she.” (5.1.315).

German colonial rule was described by many observers as brutal, especially regarding the genocide of the Ovaherero and Nama in German South West Africa. Of course, such a vast colonial empire cannot be adequately captured by a simple description. The German colonial empire was as varied in its policies and ruling styles as it was in geography. Educational provisions across the colonies were similarly diverse. When the British took control of German East Africa (Tanganyika) in 1919, they found a large population of educated and literate Africans. German educational efforts in Kamerun and other colonies were also praised by contemporary authors.

The situation in South West Africa (now Namibia) was in stark contrast. Unlike East Africa, where the government established state schools and played a significant role in educating the native population, in South West Africa, education for natives was largely left to missionary societies with limited government support. However, the government invested significant resources in educating Europeans in the colony, establishing state schools and providing more substantial support and regulation for missionary schools. These educational policies had long-lasting effects on South West Africa, even after German rule ended. While other German colonies had significant numbers of literate and educated Africans, in South West Africa, "the overwhelming majority of the population remained untouched, uneducated, and illiterate." Various social, political, and economic factors led to the different experiences of South West Africa. This paper aims to expand the discussion by identifying these factors and focusing on new research into the attitudes of settlers and colonial authorities towards native Africans.

There is a substantial body of literature specifically addressing education in the German colonial empire. Most of these sources are in German and were written in the early twentieth century, during or shortly after the period of German colonial rule. The aim of early works was primarily to describe the characteristics of educational systems in these colonies. Later writings in English expanded the discourse through comparative studies of education in the various German colonies and more detailed analyses of specific educational aspects. These studies highlighted significant differences in the educational systems of different colonies. The most notable work addressing the topic of this paper is Cohen's study of education in South West Africa and East Africa. Cohen compares the educational systems of the two colonies and discusses the factors explaining the differences between them. According to Cohen, the large settler population in South West Africa accounts for many distinctive aspects of the colony's educational system.

Compared to Germany's other colonial possessions, South West Africa had a moderately temperate climate, although much of the territory is covered by arid desert. The European population of South West Africa reflected the relatively hospitable conditions. By 1913, nearly 15,000 whites lived in South West Africa, while only 5,336 resided in the colony with the next largest settler population, East Africa.

The United States of America and Mexico serve as an example of two nations that were once entangled in a lasting rivalry lasting 57 years, from 1836 to 1893 (Diehl and Goerts 2000 p. 145). The pinnacle of this rivalry was the Mexican-American War from 1846-1848, during which the United States attacked and defeated Mexico, securing Texas and the American Southwest as new territories. Many other conflicts occurred between the two nations, eventually subsiding just before World War I. The rivalry began as Americans and Mexicans clashed over key issues such as religion, culture, and tradition, along with significant conflicts of material interests (Schmitt 1974 p. 30-31).

This situation is similar to many other nations that have a lasting rivalry with a neighbor. Nations sharing a border are prone to conflicts of interest that lead to the development of rival positions between them. The rivalry between the United States and Mexico is akin to many other enduring rivalries between nations with a common border. David M. Pletcher (1977) notes that “only in Mexico and Cuba can one find long-lasting overarching American diplomatic problems” (p. 41). Indeed, both of these nations are geographically close to the United States and have been its rivals, while other nations in Latin America have enjoyed and continue to enjoy good relations with the United States.

Religious issues created a division between the two nations, a problem that has affected many nations throughout history. Sally Frahm (2001) states that “if in the twentieth century Americans were opposed to fascism and communism, in the eighteenth and nineteenth centuries they opposed Catholicism and monarchy” (p.86). Similar to the Cold War rivalry between the United States and the Soviet Union, it was part ideological struggle and part competition over interests deemed vital by each nation. In this case, however, the ideological struggles were not based on political structures but rather on the religious preferences of the United States and Mexico. This distrust stemmed from the distrust between the English and Spanish. Inheriting these feelings of distrust from their former colonial rulers was a major obstacle in establishing amicable foreign relations between the United States and Mexico.

Diehl and Goerts (2000) list 17 disputes between Mexico and the United States during the 57-year rivalry period. Most of the disputes described by Diehl and Goerts are territorial issues relating to border raids from Mexican territory into Mexico and other frontier problems. Border raids by bandits and outlaws from American border towns were a significant issue that persisted until both the United States and Mexico exerted military force on their borders (Schmitt 1974 p. 97).

Schmitt (1974) explains that the rivalry between the two nations began to diminish as “Mexico became clearly dependent on the United States in a substantial way” (p. 109) and finally ended when American ambitions “shifted from territorial expansion to economic intervention in Mexico” (p.110) in the latter part of the 19th century.

Fifteen years ago, I was suddenly and unexpectedly disabled by an illness I never knew existed.

At that time, I was a nurse. I chose this profession from a deep-seated need for the safety and security I lacked as a child. "You'll always be able to find work; people will always get sick." This was the mantra I heard repeatedly as I reached adolescence and beyond. So, even though my dream was to be a scientist or a journalist - ideally a bit of both - I chose nursing.

Nevertheless, there I was: 46 years old, single, with no significant money in the bank, and unable to work. To this day, I remain disabled, and after 15 years of living on Social Security Disability, I literally have nothing left that I can call "mine." I get by, but every day is a struggle and an attack on my security, safety, and self-esteem. Nothing in my life is certain anymore, yet there's one thing I know to be true. I could not have managed all these years without the help of my family and a few good friends, no matter how strong I was. And believe me, when real disaster strikes, you don't feel strong at all.

My point is that there will always be emergencies in life, both big and small. There are no guarantees, and no matter how well one prepares, some things are just too big to handle on your own.

I wholeheartedly agree that we in the U.S. need to stop putting all our faith in big government's "basket"; it's moldy and falling apart anyway. Yet, I would much rather see Americans learning to trust one another again - learning to help each other and ask for help - rather than each of us individually going out to the backyard to build fallout shelters.

The conservatives in the U.S. talk about the "rugged individualism" that built this country; but in truth, what kept our forefathers going in hard times was not rugged individualism, but compassion, mutual respect, and sharing of resources. The pioneers who crossed the Rockies in wagon trains didn't make it to the coast by going it alone.

So, by all means, be prepared. I am. I have a disaster kit; first aid supplies, water purification tablets, and plastic sheeting and duct tape for the windows in case of a biological attack. I have several flashlights and all sorts of batteries, lots and lots of candles and waterproof matches, and canned goods, too. If you have the land and resources for a small farm and the ability to can or preserve your own food - do it. It's a great idea, as is a wood stove, as long as you do not live in an apartment.

But while you're at it, get to know your neighbors.

Somewhere in the fifth or sixth century BCE, a prince was born who would one day be known as Buddha. Over his lifetime, he renounced the world and became enlightened, and his teachings led to the emergence of Buddhism, the most orthodox sect of which is known as Theravada Buddhism. The religion is about two and a half millennia old; it appears different today than it did when Buddha was alive. This is evident everywhere, for example in the Theravada nation of Sri Lanka, where the annual water-cutting ceremony is observed. Both monks and laypeople participate in this ceremony, and it holds some religious significance, even though Buddha never taught about such a festivity. These differences extend from the superficial traditions to the soteriological core of the religion. The Theravada community, from both the monastic and lay perspectives, has had to adapt its doctrinal principles over time. This can be attributed to both external and internal forces, both hostile and benign.

There are several qualifying terms that this discussion will frequently use. There is the concept of internal versus external. Here, an internal force is defined as a force arising from members of the Buddhasasana, regardless of their monastic status. An external force is any force from non-Buddhists. A hostile force is any force that harms or intends to harm the Buddhist community—a force arising from a negative perception of Buddhism. A benign force is a force that does not intend to harm or help the Buddhist community—although it may end up doing one or the other as a byproduct. These terms will appear repeatedly in this discussion.

First, it is important to examine the basics of the religion—the doctrines that lie at the core of Theravada Buddhism. Buddhists seek refuge in the triple gem of the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma essentially consists of the Tripitaka—the three baskets—of Buddhist texts. The Sutta Pitaka contains all the Suttas, the Vinaya Pitaka contains the disciplinary rules, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka contains the metaphysical components of Buddhism. The metaphysical notions consist of concepts like Anatta—no soul, Dukkha—inherent suffering in life, and Anicca—impermanence of all things. Only by recognizing these concepts can one end Sansara, the cycle of death and rebirth, which happens continuously. Along with Sansara will end lobha—desire, dosa—hatred, and moha—delusion, when one becomes enlightened. In the Vinaya Pitaka, rules for life are established. For laypeople, there are five precepts (I shall not kill, I shall not lie, I shall not steal, I shall not misbehave sexually, and I shall not take intoxicating substances). For monks, there are many more disciplinary rules to follow. The most fundamental doctrinal notion in Buddhism is the notion of the four noble truths. First, Dukkha; the truth that life is suffering. Second, that attachment causes suffering. Third, that suffering can be overcome.
